1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3
{ The starting position of the Catalan. White can also begin the same with  3.Nf3  d5  4.g3  . However, playing 3.Nf3 allows the additional option of the Queen's Indian Defence, among other subtle differences.  The exact origin of the Catalan variation isn't exactly clear. However, looking through the free open-source information on the Internet, I gather that the Catalan derives its name from Catalonia after the organizers of the 1929 Barcelona tournament asked Savielly Tartakower to create a new variation in homage to the area's chess history.  The opening was, of course, played well before Tartakower's times. The Catalan is seen as a safe way to get a slight advantage. The reputation largely holds true, although, in modern times, engines have made it easier in general to find concrete equality for Black in most lines.  Among modern times, Ding Liren is a regular practitioner of the opening. Vladimir Kramnik and Boris Gelfand are a couple of other names that instantly come to mind among modern legends who have used the Catalan successfully. Apart from these regular practitioners, the opening has graced the repertoires of most of the top players in the recent past. }
3... d5 4. Bg2
{ I suggest this move over  4.Nf3  for a couple of reasons.   Firstly, in the event of  4...dxc4  , White has the additional option of  5.Qa4+  which is an important extra option to have.  Apart from that, in this repertoire, we choose to go Nd2 for the variations with ...Bb4+. In this case, with the Bishop on g2, Black usually doesn't have the additional option of ...dxc4 as White has Qa4+.   Black's play can be broadly divided into two avenues. One is where he takes  4...dxc4  . This leads to more open positions, where White is usually a pawn down but gets compensation by way of piece activity.  The variations apart from  4...dxc4  tend to be more closed by nature. }
4... dxc4
{ Amongst the first games in this position was the game Alekhine - Euwe, from their World Championship match in 1937.  The lines with  4...dxc4  is a popular choice as it leads to open positions, which many people find easier to play compared to the closed positions arising after  4...Be7  and  4...Bb4+  . }
5. Nf3
{ 5.Qa4+  is another option and a very natural move, which was also Alekhine's reply to Euwe. It is a reasonable move and one of the advantages of going with this 4.Bg2 move order is to retain the flexibility of this additional option.  However, we are not considering this in our repertoire, because I feel that it is a bit too simplistic and with the best play, ends up in drawish positions.  This is the starting position and Black has many different options here. }
5... Bd7
{ This is an underestimated and not so well-known variation. With  5...Bd7  Black looks to clear his Queenside pieces quickly and castle long.  The nature of the variation is such that it can be easy to make the initial few moves with Black, and as such is useful in games with shorter time controls, especially considering that the variation isn't well known among White players.  On a side note, this is also a pet line of my student GM Arjun Erigaisi, especially in Blitz games. Therefore I was all the more motivated to show advantage here and try to persuade him to learn some good habits... }
6. Ne5
{ White has multiple ways to get an objective advantage after 5... Bd7. I recommend 6. Ne5 because it immediately takes out Black's light-squared Bishop, which gives White a long-term strategic gain.   Black typically tends to castle long in these positions after 5... Bd7. In such positions, having an unchallenged light-squared Bishop can be very useful as the b7-pawn especially becomes a target with the Black King on c8. }
6... Bc6 7. Nxc6 Nxc6 8. O-O Qd7
{ Black is preparing to castle long and imbalance the position a bit. Going for short castle after Be7 would be too mainstream and White will have an edge thereafter building the position with e3-Qa4-Nbd2. }
9. e3
{ Although the d4-pawn isn't yet hanging, it is useful to strengthen it and vacate space for Qe2, which is a typical square for the Queen in these setups. }
9... Rd8 { Black tries to break with e5 without committing long castle. } 10.
Qe2 { Taking the Queen out of the d-file. } 10... e5 11. Qxc4
{ 11.dxe5  is not really an option in general in this position as Black can just take  11...Nxe5  , after which the c4-pawn gets well defended and Black can put his Knight on d3. }
11... exd4 12. Qb5 Rb8
{ 12...dxe3  would simply be met by  13.Bxe3  with excellent compensation. }
13. Rd1
{ White wins back the d4-pawn. Black must ensure that the d4-pawn is not taken by a piece so as to induce White to take it back with a pawn and play with an IQP. }
13... a6 14. Qc4 Bd6 15. exd4
{ The logical middlegame arising out of this variation. White has a slight edge due to his pair of Bishops. However, Black also has a solid position without many weaknesses. }
15... O-O 16. Nc3 h6 17. a3
{ White has a slight edge. However, the plan moving forward isn't straightforward and depends on how Black plays.   Right now the Rook on d1 is a bit misplaced. Ideally White should have one of the rooks on the open e-file. As such, b4, Ra2 and Re2 is one way to bring the Rook out.   It is also possible for White to open more lines for his Bishop with b4 and b5. It is useful for White to provoke Black to play ...cxb5 as it loses control over d5, which is an important strategic square.   White's intention is to not keep the pawns on a3, b4 and d4 static. That would harm the interests of his dark-squared Bishop. But if White can get the pawns to a4 and b5, then the Bishop can come out with Ba3.   White has to gradually build pressure using the parts of the boards he is controlling, and try to keep increasing the pressure along with this. Black has comparatively limited space. }
