{ 4...b5  is not the most popular line. However, it is not a bad variation, having even been played by Kasparov against Karpov in one of their matches in 2009.  The idea is simple - to hold on to the pawn on c4. When White tries to recapture the pawn by breaking on the Queenside, then Black anticipates the exchange of all the pawns on the Queenside, which leads to a position with mass simplifications. Black would then have to exchange the pawn with ...c5 in order to simplify everything and head towards a draw. }
5. a4
