1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3
{ The starting position of Catalan. White can also begin the same with  3.Nf3  d5  4.g3  . However, playing 3.Nf3 allows the additional option of the Queen's Indian defence, among other subtle differences.  The exact origin of the Catalan variation isn't exactly clear. However, looking through the free open-source information on the Internet, I gather that the Catalan derives its name from Catalonia after the organizers of the 1929 Barcelona tournament asked Savielly Tartakower to create a new variation in homage to the area's chess history.  The opening was, of course, played well before Tartakower's times. The Catalan is seen as a safe way to get a slight advantage. The reputation largely holds true, although, in modern times, engines have made it easier in general to find concrete equality for Black in most lines.  Among modern times, Ding Liren is a regular practitioner of the opening. Vladimir Kramnik and Boris Gelfand are a couple of other names that instantly come to mind among modern legends who have used Catalan successfully. Apart from these regular practitioners, the opening has graced the repertoires of most of the top players in the recent past. }
3... d5 4. Bg2
{ I suggest this move over  4.Nf3  for a couple of reasons.   Firstly, in the event of  4...dxc4  , White has the additional option of  5.Qa4+  which is an important extra option to have.  Apart from that, in this repertoire, we choose to go Nd2 for the variations with ...Bb4+. In this case, with the Bishop on g2, Black usually doesn't have the additional option of ...dxc4 as White has Qa4+.   Black's play can be broadly divided into two avenues. One is where he takes  4...dxc4  . This leads to more open positions, where White is usually a pawn down but gets compensation by way of piece activity.  The variations apart from  4...dxc4  tend to be more closed by nature. }
4... Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O
{ In this chapter, we will be looking at lines where Black plays without ...dxc4. As such, the centre will be closed, and therefore the position as well.   In the absence of ...dxc4, Black's usual plan of development is c6, Nbd7, b6 and the c8 Bishop goes to either b7 or a6. After this, Black tries to free his position with Rc8 and ...c5.   There are two main ways to start this. Black can either start with  6...Nbd7  or  6...c6 }
6... Nbd7
{ The drawback of starting with this move is that it leaves out options for Black to play ...Na6 later. This can be an important difference. }
7. Qc2
{ White continues with his usual plan of playing for e4. However, unlike in the 6... c6-variation, here it is safer to go 8. Nbd2 as Black doesn't have this option of Na6.   7...Ne4  can simply be met by  8.Nc3  which attacks d5. Black doesn't have this option of backing ...Ne4 up with ...f5 as d5 would be hanging. }
7... c6 8. Nbd2 b6 9. e4
{ The crossroads of the 6...Nbd7 variation. Black can play  9...Bb7  ,  9...Ba6  or take either of the pawns. }
9... Ba6 10. b3
{ With 9...Ba6 there is a difference, although  10.e5  is also a good move.  Firstly White can't immediately follow up with cxd5 due to the pin on the f1-Rook. Secondly, the Bishop being on a6 helps Black tactically in a lot of the variations. }
10... Rc8 11. Bb2 c5 12. exd5 exd5 13. Rfe1
{ White's moves have been seemingly quiet on the outside. However, White is subtly preparing the opening of the position.   The double fianchetto helps White control large portions on the board and the f5-square is an ideal square for the White Knight, especially when it's combined with a Bishop on b2. }
13... cxd4 14. Nxd4
{ White's Knight is always happy to get to d4, from where it eyes c6 and f5. }
14... b5 15. Nf5 { White's attack is crashing through. } 15... Re8 16. Bxd5
Nxd5 17. Nxg7
{ Although White is a piece down, he is attacking the e8-Rook.  If Black plays  17...Rf8  White just withdraws the Knight with  18.Nf5  opening up the b2-h8 diagonal and threatening  18...--  19.Nh6#   White's attacking possibilities are overwhelming. }
