3... Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3
{ It is better for White to begin with Nc3 and ensure that Black doesn't get d5 before committing the White Knight. This is because in some systems the g1-Knight can develop to e2. }
5... d6 6. Nf3 Nc6
{ The system with ...Nc6 is called the Panno-system. This setup is as old as any, with the first game dating back to Alekhine - Yates, 1923.   Black seeks to take control over the centre with a piece, Grnfeld style. The other way to challenge White's control of the centre is with pawns, in the more conventional way, with ...c6 and ...e5. }
