3. Nf3
{ White intends to keep the option of the place of development of the b1-Knight flexible. It can go to either d2 or c3 in the future.  It is also possible to start with  3.Nc3  with its own pros and cons. The move-order starting with  3.Nf3  conforms better to our setup in question. }
3... dxc4
{ This is not the most commonly played, nor the soundest move in this position. However, it has also been played in a decent amount of games and deserves consideration. }
4. e3 Be6
{ The best way to try and hold on to the pawn.  4...b5  would be met by  5.a4  followed by axb5 and b3.  Black loses the pawn back pretty quickly with the strategic features in favour of White. }
5. Nbd2
{ This is far from the most played move in this position, but is definitely the most straightforward option. White simply develops a piece and threatens to win the pawn back. Sometimes the simplest options are also the most powerful options. }
5... Qa5 6. Be2 b5 7. O-O Nf6 8. a4
{ A typical break when the opposition pawn is on b5, and a strong pawn break as well.   Having completed his development, White sets about exploiting his development advantage. The break with a4 and b3 is the typical way to go about it.   At the outset, Black's pawns on the Queenside look menacing and control too much space. If White doesn't act against them, Black can even be better after completing his development. However, the problem for Black is that those pawns are brittle. }
8... g6
{ 8...Na6  9.Ne5  Rc8  10.Ra3  is an instructive variation. White threatens axb5 and will win back the c4-pawn in one way or another.  After equalizing material, White has clear strategic superiority. The contrast between the White Knight on e5 and the Black Knight on a6 is a good symbolic illustration.   8...Nbd7  9.Ng5  leaves the Bishop on e6 in an awkward position from which it cannot get out. }
9. Ng5
{ A typical strategic operation in this setup. Taking out the light-squared Bishop further weakens all of these Black pawns on the light squares. }
9... Bd5 10. e4 h6 11. exd5 hxg5 12. dxc6
{ White has taken out the light-squared Bishop and has a pretty strong pawn on c6 himself. }
12... Nxc6 13. axb5
{ A very strong idea, also played in Lysyj - Demidov, 2016. Black cannot capture back  13...Qxb5  of course, as after  14.Bxc4  the material would be equal while White has overwhelming control over the light squares.   Black's King is also still in the centre and isn't wholly well-developed. Black is forced to take  13...Qxa1  . }
13... Qxa1 14. bxc6
{ A very strong idea. White's dangerous pawn, combined with his superior control over the light squares give very strong compensation. These are still relatively vague strategic concepts, but one of the other factors strongly in White's favour is the concept of time.   Black's Kingside is completely underdeveloped and he will require at least two moves to sort that out. On the other hand, Black's Queen is completely offside and it is not completely clear whether Black can extradite the Black Queen from White's territory without losing some material.   Therefore White is completely better and dominating. }
