{ The starting position of the Catalan. White can also begin the same with  3.Nf3  d5  4.g3  . However, playing 3.Nf3 allows the additional option of the Queen's Indian Defence, among other subtle differences.  The exact origin of the Catalan variation isn't exactly clear. However, looking through the free open-source information on the Internet, I gather that the Catalan derives its name from Catalonia after the organizers of the 1929 Barcelona tournament asked Savielly Tartakower to create a new variation in homage to the area's chess history.  The opening was, of course, played well before Tartakower's times. The Catalan is seen as a safe way to get a slight advantage. The reputation largely holds true, although, in modern times, engines have made it easier in general to find concrete equality for Black in most lines.  Among modern times, Ding Liren is a regular practitioner of the opening. Vladimir Kramnik and Boris Gelfand are a couple of other names that instantly come to mind among modern legends who have used the Catalan successfully. Apart from these regular practitioners, the opening has graced the repertoires of most of the top players in the recent past. }
3... d5 4. Bg2
{ I suggest this move over  4.Nf3  for a couple of reasons.   Firstly, in the event of  4...dxc4  , White has the additional option of  5.Qa4+  which is an important extra option to have.  Apart from that, in this repertoire, we choose to go Nd2 for the variations with ...Bb4+. In this case, with the Bishop on g2, Black usually doesn't have the additional option of ...dxc4 as White has Qa4+.   Black's play can be broadly divided into two avenues. One is where he takes  4...dxc4  . This leads to more open positions, where White is usually a pawn down but gets compensation by way of piece activity.  The variations apart from  4...dxc4  tend to be more closed by nature. }
4... Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. O-O dxc4
{ The starting position of the mainline Catalan. If I had to pick out two important aspects, it would be:   1.White's g2-bishop which is usually the most important piece   2.Black tries to get in either c5 or e5 in most positions here as a way of freeing up space. These pawn breaks are a very important factor and something we must be aware of and constantly watch out for from both sides.   6...c6  is the other option here, keeping the centre closed. }
7. Qc2 a6 8. a4
{ A relatively recent move.  8.Qxc4  was the age-old move that enables Black to develop the bishop to b7 and try to neutralize White's Catalan-Bishop.  The drawback of this move is that it weakens b4, where Black would love to park his Knight. }
8... Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Bg5
{ This starting position is almost as old as the line with 8. a4 itself. The development of the Bishop to g5 is quite logical, as e4 is the focal strategic point in this variation.   The Bishop on g5 seeks to take out the Knight on f6, thereby indirectly increasing his numbers in the fight for the control of e4.   Black has essentially two ways of fighting against this. One is to try to replace the b8-Knight @@StartBracket@@by Nbd7@@EndBracket@@ for the f6-Knight in the job of controlling e4.   The other is to temporarily fight for the control of the e4-square with the Bishop, while simultaneously trying for c5, which also effectively breaks White's central control. }
10... Bd5 11. Qc2 Be4
{ This is a typical way to play as Black. Black likes to put the Bishop on e4 here, preventing White from playing e4 himself.   On the other hand, the centralized Bishop on e4 also keeps itself flexible, keeping options to retreat to c6 if he is able to achieve c5. The e4-bishop can also retreat to h7 quite often, after h6. }
12. Qc1
{ The initial response to Be4 was to go  12.Qd1  until someone realized: why not keep the Queen on the c-file, thereby preventing c5? }
12... h6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Rd1
{ The common place for the Rook in these variations. The Rook defends the central d4-pawn, while e4 is usually adequately protected by the Knight on c3 and the Bishop on g2. }
14... a5 15. Nbd2
{ This move effectively forces Black to take on f3 as any other move allows White to get e4 in. As we will see in quite a few other variations, the White knight is well-placed on c4 here. }
15... Bxf3 16. Bxf3 c6 17. e3
{ A typical way of putting White's pawns here.  White's future is based on his Kingside play, although the central break is also not completely out of the question. White follows with h4 and Kg2. }
