9... cxb3 10. Qxb3 c6 11. O-O
{ A typical Catalan position where White is a pawn down. However, the compensation White gets in such positions is much more than the compensation Black gets in Benko Gambit type of positions, where Black gets similar counterplay across open lines on the Queenside, but lacks the kind of strategically weak squares that the White's Knight has access to here.   Black's pawns have been forced on to the light squares, and these pawns are not easy to advance on the Queenside. White has a good Catalan Bishop on g2, and the squares c5 and e5 for his Knight, apart from the semi-open b- and c- file for the Rooks.   White has ample compensation and I think it is much easier to play from White in these type of positions. }
11... O-O 12. Rfc1 { The typical position for the White Rook in this setup. }
12... Bb7 13. Qb2
{ It is important to protect d4, and b2 is the ideal square from which the Queen can do it.   This also frees up the b3-square for the White Knight from which it can reach c5, and can be a general, useful prophylactic move as well.   The Queen is also less likely to be attacked with a tempo on b2 than on b3. }
