1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
{ The King's Indian Fianchetto variation. White's first four moves for the Catalan and the King's Indian defence are identical.   Like the Catalan, the King's Indian defence, Fianchetto variation has a solid reputation. This method of development is on completely different lines than other King's Indian variations. Here, Black's normal plan of attack can hardly succeed, as White's kingside is more solidly defended than in most KID variations. }
3... Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3
{ It is better for White to begin with Nc3 and ensure that Black doesn't get d5 before committing the White Knight. This is because in some systems the g1-Knight can develop to e2. }
5... d6 6. Nf3 Nc6
{ The system with ...Nc6 is called the Panno-system. This setup is as old as any, with the first game dating back to Alekhine - Yates, 1923.   Black seeks to take control over the centre with a piece, Grnfeld style. The other way to challenge White's control of the centre is with pawns, in the more conventional way, with ...c6 and ...e5. }
7. O-O
{ The starting position. Black has many different ways to respond from here. Black's plans mostly revolve around breaking White's centre which can be done by ...e5 or ...b5. }
7... e5
{ Aside from the ...b5-break, this is the other most common break that Black seeks to achieve with the Panno-system. It is also arguably one of the most logical ways to follow up ...Nc6 with.   However, the positions following this can lead to plain positions, especially if White takes dxe5 which is what we intend to do in this repertoire. This can be against what Black players aim for when playing the King's Indian Defence. }
8. dxe5
{ One of the simplest ways to fight for an advantage.   It is tempting for White to go into the exchange King's Indian setups with the Black Knight on c6. This is because in the exchange King's Indian setup, typically the d5- and b5-squares are targets for the White Knight.   Black can usually neutralize this with ...c6. However, in this case, the Black Knight is already on c6 which makes it practically inconvenient to put the pawn on c6. }
8... dxe5
{ The best move. Although the position remains symmetrical the ensuing middlegame can get very complex and Black can generate counterplay. }
9. Bg5
{ The most natural follow up to dxe5. White's first pressure point is on the g5-d8 diagonal with Bg5 combined with Nd5. }
9... Be6 10. Qa4
{ The White Queen makes way for the Rook to come to d1 and aim for Nd5, putting pressure on Black. Nd2/Nde4 is also another common way to put pressure on Black.   As common in this setup, the squares d5, c5 and b5 are the vulnerable squares for Black. If Black could, Black would happily put the c6-Knight on d7 and the pawn on c6. However, it is too late to do this. }
10... h6
{ Black attempts to solve his problem with the most concrete and direct means by forcing White to take Bxf6 instead of waiting for White to do it at a convenient moment for himself. }
11. Rad1
{ It might be paradoxical to play the Rook on a1 to d1 instead of the Rook on f1.   However, the Rook on f1 is actually very necessary on f1 and will play a useful and important role later, especially against ...f5 and ...e4 by Black. }
11... Qe8
{ 11...Qc8  will simply be met by  12.Bxf6  Bxf6  13.Nd2  after which White has that typical advantage.   After  11...Qe8  it's useful for Black to get in ...Nd4. e3 can be responded to with ...Ne2+ in this case. If White exchanges the Queen first after ...Nd4 then the c4-pawn would be hanging. }
12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Nd5
{ Playing in the typical spirit of this variation.  13.Nd2  is also possible, but Black doesn't have a lot of problems after  13...Nd4  14.Nde4  Bg7  .  White also has to worry about the e2- and the c4-pawns and there is not enough time to play e3 here due to a ...Ne2+, which illustrates the usefulness of placing the Black Queen on e8. }
13... Bd8 14. Qb3 Bc8
{ Black can try  14...f5  here and  15.Qxb7  would be met by  15...Rb8  , hitting b2.   However, after  14...f5  White has  15.e4!  and if Black takes  15...fxe4  then White gets a comfortable position with a great place for the Knights and a good pawn structure after  16.Nd2  followed by Nxe4.  If Black responds with @@StartFEN@@r2bqrk1/ppp2p2/2n1b1pp/3Np3/2P5/1Q3NP1/PP2PPBP/3R1RK1 b - - 3 14@@EndFEN@@  14...f5  15.e4  with  15...f4  , then after  16.gxf4  exf4  17.Rfe1  White threatens to move in with e5, with a very strong position. }
15. c5
{ White has managed to push the Black's pieces away for now. However, Black's main counter-play remains ...f5 and ...e4. White has to be vigilant about this and try to prevent this from happening.   15.c5  helps towards this direction as it prevents Black from playing ...f5 and  15.c5  is also a useful improving move in general. }
15... a5
{ Black doesn't have a suitable follow up after  15...e4  16.Nd2  . Therefore he tries to gain space for the moment and also dislodge the White Queen from b3 which can free the c8-Bishop. }
16. h3
{ White intends e4 later in order to strengthen the White Knight on d5 and prevent all f5, e4 possibilities for Black. It is important to prevent Black from playing ...Bg4 before White goes e4 and h3 helps prepare towards that. }
16... a4 17. Qc4
{ White has a slightly better position with good control over the board and over the activity of Black's pieces.   Typically after e4, White can try to get b4 and b5 in to gain more control over the d4-square. The White Queen is usually well placed on c3. Black is deprived of his King's Indian activity and cannot get that active play he is more accustomed to. }
