8. e4 exd4
{ With this setup, Black clarifies his intention in the centre immediately. Black can of course play  8...c6  and delay this idea, which leads to another mainline. }
9. Nxd4 Re8 10. h3
{ A very useful move in general in the fianchetto setup of the King's Indian defence. This is something similar to the Kb1/Kh1 moves made in various Sicilian defence setups. It is hard to innumerate exactly how this helps and in how many ways.   The most direct function is, of course, the prevention of ...Ng4 which can be a useful move for Black in many positions. However, the usefulness of h3 is not just limited to that. While it is hard to concretely point out the number of ways it is useful, it suffices to say that it is one of those general useful moves that one makes on auto-pilot  }
10... Nc5
{ Black's play centres around the ...b5-break. With ...Nc5, Black commits the Knight to c5. The Black Knight has at least two good squares to go to from d7 - e5 and c5. Although c5 is the more preferred square for the Knight in this setup usually, there does exist some systems where the Black Knight can also go to e5.   Any such activity on the flank related to ...b5 also indirectly contributes towards the play in the centre, as ...b4 kicks the Knight away from c3 which is controlling the centre. }
11. Re1
{ At the moment, White's centre is well-defended and under control.   However, White needs to be cautious and watch out for any such counterplay in the centre. Black gets tactics related to the e4- and d4-square in many variations so White should always watch out for these things. }
11... a5
{ ...a5 at this juncture before White has played Rb1 or b3 is premature. This weakens the b5-square and allows White to develop Bf4 in one tempo which puts Black's c7- and d6-squares under pressure. }
12. Ndb5 { White strikes on the b5-square while it is hot. } 12... Bd7 13. Bf4
{ Nxc7, Bxd6 and e5 are the actual threats in this position that Black has to watch out for. }
13... Bxb5 14. cxb5
{ The only move as  14.Nxb5  would lose the e4-pawn.  But a good exchange for White, opening up the c-file and weakening Black's c7-pawn. }
14... Nfd7 15. Qc2
{ Getting into the line of sight of the c-file and strengthening control over e4. }
15... h5
{ Black wants to provoke White's pawns on the light squares and take control of the dark squares weakened as a consequence. For example, ...h4 g4 .. .g5. }
16. Be3
{ A prophylactic move that moves away from any direct attacks coming from ...g5. White also prepares f4. }
16... h4 17. g4 g5 18. Rf1
{ White's next move is set to be f4 which will ensure that Black doesn't have a bind on the dark squares. At the moment, White's fixture of pawns on the light squares seems unfortunate. However, these are not permanent fixtures and White has the room to open up his pawns with moves like f4 and e5.   Black has made some strategic moves in order to try and secure the dark squares. However, this has also weakened the light squares in Black's position.   White has a light square Bishop and Black doesn't, so if White gets into a situation where he can sacrifice something like e5 and play something like Qf5 and Be4, then Black won't be able to ward off those threats easily. e5 is a popular and attractive possibility to make a strategic sacrifice in this position. }
