1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3
{ The starting position of the Catalan. White can also begin the same with  3.Nf3  d5  4.g3  . However, playing 3.Nf3 allows the additional option of the Queen's Indian Defence, among other subtle differences.  The exact origin of the Catalan variation isn't exactly clear. However, looking through the free open-source information on the Internet, I gather that the Catalan derives its name from Catalonia after the organizers of the 1929 Barcelona tournament asked Savielly Tartakower to create a new variation in homage to the area's chess history.  The opening was, of course, played well before Tartakower's times. The Catalan is seen as a safe way to get a slight advantage. The reputation largely holds true, although, in modern times, engines have made it easier in general to find concrete equality for Black in most lines.  Among modern times, Ding Liren is a regular practitioner of the opening. Vladimir Kramnik and Boris Gelfand are a couple of other names that instantly come to mind among modern legends who have used the Catalan successfully. Apart from these regular practitioners, the opening has graced the repertoires of most of the top players in the recent past. }
3... d5 4. Bg2
{ I suggest this move over  4.Nf3  for a couple of reasons.   Firstly, in the event of  4...dxc4  , White has the additional option of  5.Qa4+  which is an important extra option to have.  Apart from that, in this repertoire, we choose to go Nd2 for the variations with ...Bb4+. In this case, with the Bishop on g2, Black usually doesn't have the additional option of ...dxc4 as White has Qa4+.   Black's play can be broadly divided into two avenues. One is where he takes  4...dxc4  . This leads to more open positions, where White is usually a pawn down but gets compensation by way of piece activity.  The variations apart from  4...dxc4  tend to be more closed by nature. }
4... Bb4+
{ 4...Bb4+  is one of the most solid systems against the Catalan. This motif of Bb4+ before bringing back the Bishop to e7 is a typical strategic operation Black does in a few 1.d4-lines.  The idea of luring the Bishop to d2 is multi-fold. It feels a bit paradoxical that the White Bishop is placed worse at d2 compared to c1. For starters, it takes away the d2 spot from the b1-Knight. The d2-Bishop impedes Queen's vision of d4. Although this isn't often relevant, it does make a difference in some rare variations.  It is also common for White to go b3, a4 in many lines in this Catalan pawn structure in which case, the Bishop on c1 has the additional options to go to b2 and a3 apart from the usual f4. }
5. Nd2
{ 5.Nd2  isn't the most popular option after the Bb4+ setups.  5.Bd2  is more popular. However, in this repertoire, I have chosen to go towards the direction of Nd2 against both @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/6P1/PP2PPBP/RNBQK1NR b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Bb4+  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/2PP4/6P1/PP2PP1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Bb4+  for a few reasons:  1. The positions after Nd2 are relatively simpler and therefore easier to play;  2. With objectively best play, Black manages to equalize in both  5.Nd2  and  5.Bd2  in more than one way;  3. Variations with Nd2 are relatively less explored and therefore leads to fresher positions.  Therefore, I felt that going for the simpler and fresher positions would be more interesting. }
5... O-O
{ Black can also play  5...a5  here, which will transpose to the otherlines with 6...a5 after, for example,  6.Nf3  O-O  7.O-O  . @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/6P1/PP1NPPBP/R1BQK1NR b KQkq - 3 5@@EndFEN@@  5...O-O  comes in pretty much all the variations.   An important advantage with the Bishop on g2 is that Black cannot take  5...dxc4  due to  6.Qa4+  . With the White Knight on f3, @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/1bPP4/5NP1/PP1NPP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4  would be a strong move, which is one of the important reasons why we choose to start with 4.Bg2 in this repertoire. }
