{ It is better for White to begin with Nc3 and ensure that Black doesn't get d5 before committing the White Knight. This is because in some systems the g1-Knight can develop to e2. }
5... d6 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. O-O e5
{ Black makes a push towards challenging White's central pawns. Although Black cannot match the number of pawns in White's centre by sheer number, Black can try to neutralize White's control with a combination of his pawns and pieces.   In this setup most often Black continues with ...exd4, so the actual pressure will be on the e-pawn. }
8. e4 exd4
{ With this setup, Black clarifies his intention in the centre immediately. Black can of course play  8...c6  and delay this idea, which leads to another mainline. }
