{ The starting position of the Catalan. White can also begin the same with  3.Nf3  d5  4.g3  . However, playing 3.Nf3 allows the additional option of the Queen's Indian Defence, among other subtle differences.  The exact origin of the Catalan variation isn't exactly clear. However, looking through the free open-source information on the Internet, I gather that the Catalan derives its name from Catalonia after the organizers of the 1929 Barcelona tournament asked Savielly Tartakower to create a new variation in homage to the area's chess history.  The opening was, of course, played well before Tartakower's times. The Catalan is seen as a safe way to get a slight advantage. The reputation largely holds true, although, in modern times, engines have made it easier in general to find concrete equality for Black in most lines.  Among modern times, Ding Liren is a regular practitioner of the opening. Vladimir Kramnik and Boris Gelfand are a couple of other names that instantly come to mind among modern legends who have used the Catalan successfully. Apart from these regular practitioners, the opening has graced the repertoires of most of the top players in the recent past. }
3... Bb4+
{ This is one of the best and most solid options against the Catalan move order. It is especially useful for Black to play with this  3...Bb4+  move order because after  4.Nd2  Black has this additional option of  4...c5  , which is important. }
4. Nd2 c5
{ Black has essentially two ways to play here. The lines involving ...d5 can happen directly, or after  4...O-O  and then 5...d5, which is covered in the chapter with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/2PP4/6P1/PP2PP1P/RNBQKBNR b KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...d5  and 4...Bb4+.   This was one of the most difficult lines for me when making this repertoire. To be honest, @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/6P1/PP1NPP1P/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  4...c5  equalizes completely with correct play at the highest level, and I could find no way for White to even obtain a slight edge.  However, even at the highest level, it is a challenge to remember all the lines and details clearly, despite the players constantly revising their notes.  Therefore, the recommendation I have given in this repertoire leads to an equal endgame with precise play by Black. }
5. a3
{ This is the most principled line. White immediately forces Black to exchange his Bishop for the Knight, gaining the pair of Bishops. }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2
{ White is forced to capture with the Queen as recapturing with  6.Bxd2  would be met by  6...cxd4  . That pawn isn't easily recapturable by White as Black can defend it with ...Nc6 and ...e5.  The drawback is that this impedes the development of the c1-Bishop. But the Bishop usually comes out from b2 just fine in such situations, especially after the d4-pawn gets exchanged. }
6... cxd4 7. Nf3
{ White would prefer to capture on d4 with the Knight if it is concretely possible. }
7... Nc6 8. Nxd4
{ White is forced to take this pawn immediately as Black had a direct threat of ...e5. }
8... Na5
{ A critical move. Black threatens ...Nxc4 as well as ...e5 which implies the threat of Nb3. }
9. Qb4
{ White has managed to defend against both the threats and also control ...Qb6 and prevent Black's O-O. However, this also leaves the Queen open to being harassed by Black's Knight to d5. }
9... d5 10. e4
{ A very strong move. Looking at it, one might get the impression that it is one of those crazy computer moves. However, this was played as early as in 1983, by GM Mikhalchisin.   The idea is that White opens up the Bishops in a position where Black has been prevented from castling. Taking the pawn is dangerous for Black as White gets his pieces into action with tempo. }
10... Nxc4 11. exd5 exd5 12. Nb5
{ Having restricted the Black King from castling, White threatens Bxc4 and Nd6+. Black has to react concretely against White's threats. }
12... a5
{ 12...a5 creates space for the Rook and prepares ...Qe7+.   12...Qe7+  directly would be met by  13.Qxe7+  Kxe7  14.Nc7  Rb8  15.Bf4  with the threat of Nxd5+. }
13. Qc5 Qe7+ 14. Qxe7+ Kxe7 15. Nc7
{ Here Black has the additional option of  15...Ra7  , which is the point of including a5.   15...Ra7  would be met by  16.b3  followed by Bb2, unleashing the pair of Bishops on an open board.   15...Rb8  would be met by  16.Bf4  threatening a discovered check with Nxd5+. }
