5... d6 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. O-O e5
{ Black makes a push towards challenging White's central pawns. Although Black cannot match the number of pawns in White's centre by sheer number, Black can try to neutralize White's control with a combination of his pawns and pieces.   In this setup most often Black continues with ...exd4, so the actual pressure will be on the e-pawn. }
8. e4 c6
{ This is Black's classic setup against the Fianchetto setup of King's Indian. White has built up an imposing centre.   Black aims to put pressure against the centre with a combination of his pawns and pieces. }
9. h3 { A typical prophylactic move in the King's Indian Defence. } 9... Qb6
10. Re1
{ Statistically the most played move in this position and therefore the mainline. I have found this the simplest to play as White and I haven't really felt comfortable with Black's position. }
10... Re8 11. d5
{ This pawn structure is distinctly different from the positions with the ...exd4 pawn structure. White's play is largely on the kingside and the centre in the systems with ...exd4, as that is where White has more space in that pawn structure.   With the centre closed here with d5, White also has superior space and control in the Queenside, and it is more natural for White to play on the Queenside here. Black can carry on with ...cxd5 or without cxd5. }
11... Nc5
{ With the Queen on b6, and the pawn likely to come to a5, the Black Knight gets a nice and safe haven on the Queenside. }
12. Rb1
{ Intending to evict the Knight with b4 and also to develop the c1-Bishop. }
12... a5 13. Be3
{ The standard place for the Bishop in these systems in general. It is quite common for White to transfer the Knight from f3 to c4 in this setup and Be3 enables that by getting out of the way in advance. }
13... Qc7 14. Nd2
{ Although the c4-square isn't readily available for the Knight yet, at some point, there are good prospects of Black taking ...cxd5 and White prepare himself for that.   If Black never commits it, White can gradually begin to start playing for b3, a3 and b4 himself, gradually gaining more ground on the Queenside. }
14... Bd7 { Black intends to play b5, without having committed to ...cxd5. }
15. Bf1
{ White also prepares against Black's ...b5 with useful moves that increase the control of the Queenside anyway. This position has similarities with the Ruy Lopez system. At least Black's central and Kingside pawns are exactly identical. However, it is a version of Ruy Lopez that is much better for White as White has clearly superior control of the Queenside here and more control in the centre as well, which is usually under much more pressure in the Ruy Lopez positions. }
15... Rec8 16. b3 Qd8
{ By taking the Queen away from c7, Black actually prepares ...cxd5 cxd5 ...b5, as if White takes the b5-pawn, he would lose the e4-pawn.   Black also prepares ideas like ...Qf8 and ...Bh6 in an effort to activate/exchange his Bad Bishop. }
17. Bxc5
{ A typical idea in such structures, intended to damage Black's pawn structure.   This is also an idea that exists in the Ruy Lopez Breyer in a position where Black's centre and Kingside pawns are identically placed.   White loses the dark-squared Bishop but in exchange gets a protected passed d-pawn and a much better pawn structure. }
17... dxc5 18. Nf3 Ne8 19. Qd3
{ The position is slow and strategic in nature. At the moment White's play is in the centre and the Kingside, as the Queenside play is relatively closed.   White especially has good prospects on the d-file as he holds the key to open the file. Qe3, Rbd1, Rd3 and Red1 would be a good way to develop White's play further. h4 is a useful move in general.   After White builds up the pieces on the d-file while keeping an eye on e5 and c5, White may consider taking dxc6 at a good opportune moment at a time of his convenience and choosing.   Black has nothing much to do but to wait for White. In that sense, Black is under siege with no counter-play of his own. This is not an optimal situation to be in. Therefore, White is better and playing for two results. }
