{ The Benko/Volga Gambit, named after the Hungarian-American Grandmaster Pal Benko, who used it quite a bit in the late '60s and '70s.   The opening was quite popular in the second half of the 20th century and a bit in the early 2000s too, but as chess engines became stronger, the opening's popularity waned. In today's time, the opening is used at a higher-level when Black usually is in a situation where Black has to win on demand.   However, the opening remains popular at club-level and higher-level in shorter time controls. Black sacrifices a pawn but receives easy development of the pieces and open lines on the Queenside. }
4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bxa6
{ The natural reaction of Black and the older mainline. In more recent times, Black has found benefits in delaying the recapture of the pawn with the Bishop with ...Bxa6. }
7. g3
{ We have a version of the Benko Gambit in which White plays in a more principled manner for the repertoire.  The system with g3 is not the most optimal way to fight against the Benko Gambit in general. However, in the lines where Black has committed to ...Bxa6 early, White can obtain a healthy advantage with the g3-setup as well.  It is necessary and important to know how to play in this setup as well because Black can start out with various move orders that can transpose to this setup. For example, there are lines starting out with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d6  and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  g6   In many move-orders, Black can transpose to some version of the Benko Gambit or the Leningrad Dutch in positions where White has already committed to g3. As such, the knowledge here can come extremely handy. }
7... Bg7 8. Bg2 d6 9. Nf3
{ This is the second position that we need to be familiar with in the g3 Benko Gambit. The other being the position where Black has not committed to ...Bxa6 which is the mainline ofthis chapter. }
9... Nbd7 10. Rb1
{ A very useful defensive move and the precise move-order. If White starts with  10.O-O  then Black has the additional option of  10...Nb6  11.Rb1  Bc4  which offer Black good counterplay.   By starting with  10.Rb1  White can respond to  10...Nb6  with  11.b3 }
10... O-O 11. O-O Qa5
{ The mainline. However, this setup isn't as popular as it used to be. Something like  11...Nb6  can simply be met by  12.b3  allowing White comfortable development. }
12. Bd2
{ The standard response against ...Qa5 in the Benko Gambit.   Although White doesn't immediately threaten anything through the discovered attack, this is something useful to have in general. For example in some concrete variations, it defends against ...Nxd5.   Black usually will have to move the Queen away from a5 before playing ...Nb6.   12.Bd2  also helps defend the c3-Knight, which is important as b3 is part of the key defensive setup for White on the Queenside. }
12... Rfb8 13. Qc2
{ White's typical defensive setup on the Queenside, protecting the c3-Knight and preparing b3. }
13... Qc7 14. b3
{ White has achieved the ideal defensive setup on the Queenside. The general strategic aim for White in this structure is to get e4/e5 in. However, this usually requires preparation. For example, h3 might be necessary and important to prevent ...Ng4/...Nge5 }
14... Nb6 15. Nh4
{ The most efficient way to defend the d5-pawn. Ne1/Nd3/Nf4 is another option, but concretely this works better.   The Knight on h4 can also be useful for a jump to f5 in the future in certain variations, as we shall see in the main course. }
