1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5
{ The Albin counter-gambit. Adolf Albin played it first against Emanuel Lasker in 1893.   Although he lost that game, he stuck to his gambit for several years and his name got immortalized with the opening.   In today's time, Alexander Morozevich has played a few games here, but mostly in blitz games. As with a lot of other sidelines, it can be effective when White doesn't have a clearly defined idea of how he wants to play. }
3. dxe5 d4 4. Nf3 Nc6
{ Black generally intends to go after the e5-pawn immediately after the gambit.   If Black manages to get into a position where he is able to capture the e5-pawn without losing the d4-pawn, then Black will have equal material while the d4-pawn gives Black space.   Therefore White initially tries to go after the d4-pawn. }
5. a3
{ This is a useful prophylactic move in general. Especially in situations where Black has the possibility to play ...Bb4+, which is a very useful tool for Black to develop rapidly and interrupt White's development.   It also helps White to play b4 and Bb2, which helps put pressure on d4, which is the default strategy of White against the gambit. }
5... Nge7
{ Black is likely to follow up with Ng6, Be7 and O-O trying to put pressure on the e5-pawn. }
6. b4
{ White counters Black's intention to put pressure on e5 by preparing to put pressure on the d4-pawn. }
