15. c5
{ White has managed to push the Black's pieces away for now. However, Black's main counter-play remains ...f5 and ...e4. White has to be vigilant about this and try to prevent this from happening.   15.c5  helps towards this direction as it prevents Black from playing ...f5 and  15.c5  is also a useful improving move in general. }
15... a5
{ Black doesn't have a suitable follow up after  15...e4  16.Nd2  . Therefore he tries to gain space for the moment and also dislodge the White Queen from b3 which can free the c8-Bishop. }
16. h3
{ White intends e4 later in order to strengthen the White Knight on d5 and prevent all f5, e4 possibilities for Black. It is important to prevent Black from playing ...Bg4 before White goes e4 and h3 helps prepare towards that. }
16... a4 17. Qc4
{ White has a slightly better position with good control over the board and over the activity of Black's pieces.   Typically after e4, White can try to get b4 and b5 in to gain more control over the d4-square. The White Queen is usually well placed on c3. Black is deprived of his King's Indian activity and cannot get that active play he is more accustomed to. }
