{ The Leningrad Dutch is something that is very useful for this repertoire. Although against the direct Dutch move order, the variation with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  f5  2.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@which is my main recommendation@@EndBracket@@ is effective, Black has a number of move-order tricks at his disposal in other variations like King's Indian and Benoni, which can bring the game to this variation and this position in particular.  Therefore, knowing what to do here can be very useful for White. }
6... d6
{ The mainline. This is pretty much the King's Indian defence setup for Black except that Black has the pawn on f5 instead of f7. This is a very interesting setup that I have tried with Black quite a few times myself.   Like many offbeat variations, these lines tend to be effective when the White player has not paid much attention to how to play against these variations. And this has been the case in a lot of my own games with Black when the White player wasn't as well-prepared as he/she might be for the mainline.   Inthis chapter, I'll try to clearly explain how White should be playing in the simplest manner possible. }
7. O-O
{ White develops normally. Black has fundamentally two ways to take the game forward here. One is the plan with ...c6. The other is to put the Knight on c6. In either case, Black tries to play for ...e5.   For White, the one simple instruction is to try and meet ...e5 with e4. Black often responds to e4 with ...f4 which keeps Black's activity going. But in instances where White can play this e4 without allowing Black to play ...f4, White usually gets a very good position. }
7... c6
{ This is one of the more solid options for Black in this position. Black takes more control over the centre and this move also enables Black to play  8.--  Ne4  as against  9.Nxe4  fxe4  10.Ng5  , Black can support the e4-pawn with  10...d5  , which wouldn't be possible without the pawn on c6. }
8. Qb3
{ At the outset a normal, developing move, intending to get the Queen out of the way to connect and develop the Rooks. However, the functions of Qb3 are much more flexible than that.   Although White doesn't exactly threaten a lot with a discovered check with something like c5+ at the moment, it could possibly be useful at some other time in the future. Qb3 also takes control of d5, thereby indirectly discouraging Black from playing ...Ne4. }
8... Kh8 9. Re1
{ An unusual follow up to Qb3. It is much more common to follow up Qb3 with Rd1. However, White merely makes use of the flexibility that Qb3 offers. The Black King is slightly better placed on h8 than g8 for White's purposes.   As such White favourably transposes the position into the variation with 8. Re1 Ne4, except with the Black King on h8 instead of g8.   Playing Qb3 and combining Re1 with this move order also eliminates possibilities like 8. Re1 Na6, which is a popular way to deal with this plan of Re1 and e4 on the 8th move. }
9... Ne4 10. Qc2 Nxc3 11. bxc3
{ White intends to continue on with e4.  11.bxc3  only strengthens White's centre and opens up access to Ba3 in the future.  White is better and there have been two correspondence games here between two reasonably high rated players, which were both won by White in games that were not played too long ago. If Black was unable to defend this position with the assistance of powerful engines, that is convincing proof that White has a good position.  White's play is considerably simple and straightforward. e4 is unstoppable.  11...e5  12.e4  f4  wouldn't be attractive to Black in this position as after  13.gxf4  exf4  14.Ba3  White threatens to break on with e5. Black's d6-pawn would become weakened and White's dark-squared Bishop is a powerful piece in this position. }
