1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4
{ The Queen's Gambit accepted is an opening that stretches back all the way. Searching through the Mega Database, there are quite a few games of Greco - NN and Philidor.   The variation was extensively discussed in the 1834 match between De Labourdonnais - McDonnell. The reputation of the opening has varied over time, but it has always had a solid reputation, and that is also the case at present.   In the recent past, it has been used with reasonable frequency by several world champions and legends like Karpov, Anand, Kasparov, and was also Fischer's choice in his return match against Spassky in 1992.   In the present times, it is played by several elite players with reasonable regularity. Caruana used this with solid effect for some of his games, and the variation is also frequently played by Alekseenko, Harikrishna among many others at the elite. }
3. Nf3
{ One of the three main options for White at this move. The other moves are  3.e4  and  3.e3  , both of which can run into  3...e5  aside from Black's other options.  It makes the most sense for White to play  3.Nf3  in this repertoire as Black can enter QGA from @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  dxc4  which will transpose into this move-order.   Although  3.Nf3  retains the flexibility to go e4 or e3, White usually continues with the e3-setup much more often after playing  3.Nf3  .  After  3.Nf3  , White has to contend with  3...a6  and  3...Nf6  4.e3  Bg4  , both of which are popular alternatives for Black.   However, both these lines lead to a pleasant position for White and it is easier for White to face this rather than  3.e3  e5  in my opinion, even if White has to know a bit more in the process. }
3... a6
{ A generally useful move in the QGA which can also transpose to the mainline if Black plays  ...Nf6  and  ...c5  . However, Black can also respond with  4.e3  b5  which goes into a popular sub variation.   Apart from the variation after  3...Nf6  4.e3  Bg4  , this variation is also considered to be one of the annoying sidelines against QGA. }
4. e3 b5
{ 4...b5  is not the most popular line. However, it is not a bad variation, having even been played by Kasparov against Karpov in one of their matches in 2009.  The idea is simple - to hold on to the pawn on c4. When White tries to recapture the pawn by breaking on the Queenside, then Black anticipates the exchange of all the pawns on the Queenside, which leads to a position with mass simplifications. Black would then have to exchange the pawn with ...c5 in order to simplify everything and head towards a draw. }
5. a4
{ White's default response whenever Black plays ...b5 on the Queenside without having developed the other pieces.   The other logical move would be b3, but it makes sense to weaken the b5-pawn first before playing b3. }
5... Bb7 6. b3
{ A lot of games have included  6.axb5  axb5  in this position before playing b3.  However, I wouldn't advise this as it is more beneficial for White to keep the a-pawns, which would reduce simplification and increase White's chances of fighting for an advantage. }
6... e6 7. bxc4 bxc4 8. Bxc4
{ The material is equal with White slightly better-developed. The position is almost symmetrical, but the subtleties actually make a big difference practically. }
8... c5
{ The typical freeing move that helps Black equalize in many  1. d4 systems. Black can also start with  8...Nf6  and then play ...c5, which would transpose.  The ...c5-break is essential for Black from a strategic point of view to fight for control. }
9. O-O Nf6 10. Nbd2
{ The Knight belongs on d2 in this variation because on c3, it is vulnerable to various attacks.  For example  10.Nc3  cxd4  and then ...Qc7 or instances where the Knight on c3 can be attacked by ...Bb4 with a tempo. }
10... cxd4
{ It is actually dangerous and bold of Black to invite the White Knight on d4 as it allows all kinds of sacrifices on e6. }
11. Nxd4
{ A setup similar to the Sozin setups in the Sicilian defence, eying the e6-pawn. }
11... Nbd7
{ In the Sicilian Sozin setups, Bxe6 is usually not a threat when the Black Bishop is on f8. Here, however, this is not the case.   White gains a lot strategically by taking out Black's dark-squared Bishop, which goes into an opposite-coloured Bishop position where Black's king is exposed and vulnerable. }
12. Bxe6 { Boom } 12... fxe6 13. Nxe6 Qb6
{ 13...Qe7  isn't a good idea due to  14.Nc7+ } 14. Nxf8 Kxf8 15. Rb1 Qc7 16.
e4
{ White aims at Ba3 and Qb3+. Doing it directly allows Black to interpose with ...Bd5. Therefore, e4 takes control of the d5-square.   It is of course not possible for Black to take on e4 as  16...Nxe4  runs into  17.Ba3+  Kf7  18.Qb3+   16...Nxe4  17.Ba3+  Ke8  would run into  18.Nxe4!  exploiting Black's vulnerable king.   16...Bxe4  17.Ba3+  Kf7  18.Nxe4  Nxe4  19.Qd5+  just wins back the piece in a very advantageous situation.  The reason why this is so effective is that Black cannot prevent the White Bishop from wreaking havoc on the a3-f8 diagonal on the dark squares.  On the light squares, Black's light-squared Bishop isn't able to protect it's King on the b3-g8 diagonal. These are the concrete reasons why the  Bxe6  sacrifice is so powerful and why this gives such strong long-term compensation for White. }
