1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5
{ This is called The Budapest Gambit or The Budapest defence. The line had its first outing in 1896 but the first major clash in this battleground was Rubinstein - Vidmar and Black managed to win that game.   It got a bit popular in the 1920s where many strong players such as Richard Reti played it, but it was Tartakower who took it to the next level as he used to play it quite often and had impressive results with it.   Nowadays it is mostly played in blitz games at the top level. The game Aronian - Ivanchuk, Candidates 2013 which was won by White very convincingly is instructive. It has been played many times in 2020 due to the huge amount of online games with shorter time control in that year.   It is a direct attempt from Black to create some sort of mess and get into some unclear situation for either side but modern computers show a clear way to play and get an advantage against it. }
3. dxe5
{ Accepting the gambit is most logical. There are some games where White had declined the pawn but I found much better opportunities for White after accepting the pawn. }
3... Ng4
{ Threatening to take on e5. There are several approaches for White now.  The fourth World Champion Alekhine Alexander introduced  4.e4  , the idea was that Black can take back the pawn, but has to make many moves with the Knight. At the same time, White will be developing his pieces and take more control over the centre.  Long story short, White is willing to give the pawn back and gain a fine lead in-development but somehow this idea is not been so popular lately.  Another way of playing is also the most obvious, protect the pawn on e5. To do so, White has two different options  4.Nf3  and  4.Bf4  . }
4. Bf4
{ If White starts with  4.Nf3  Black can play  4...Bc5  after which  5.e3  is forced.  White will not have the option of Bf4 in this variation and Black is able to recapture the e5-pawn after Nc6 and Qe7. Therefore, I think Bf4 is a bit more precise. }
4... Nc6 5. Nf3 Bb4+
{ This check can be a bit annoying for White. White needs to clarify his intentions between Nc3 and Nd2 now and Black doesn't have any other good square for his Bishop anyway.   5...Bc5  6.e3  wouldn't worry White as White wants to play e3 anyway and Black would like to have the Bishop on Bb4 to prevent White's Knight from getting to d5. }
6. Nc3
{ 6.Nbd2  Qe7  7.e3  Ngxe5  8.Nxe5  Nxe5  9.Be2  +/= is another way to get a slightly better position but Nc3 is the more ambitious try.  Now White always has Qd5 to strengthen the pawn on e5 while after Nbd2, White won't have this option. }
6... Bxc3+
{ This is almost a forced move. Some calmer moves like  6...O-O  would be met by  7.h3  and now the Knight has to retreat to  7...Nh6  which will force the Black Knight to an ungainly score and also remove the pressure on the e5-pawn.   If Black tries to put pressure on the e5-pawn with  6...Qe7  , it can be met by  7.Qb3  and Black can't take on e5 as the b4-Bishop will be hanging at the end of the variation. }
7. bxc3 Qe7 { Black cannot afford to lose a tempo. } 8. Qd5
{ An important move which helps White defend the e5-pawn and to stabilize his advantage.   The Queen on d5 is safe as all the squares from where it can be attacked are controlled by the White pieces. }
8... Qa3 { Is an interesting alternative. } 9. Rb1
{ A strong and deep move. The idea is to ensure that Black cannot play  9...Qxc3+  10.Bd2  Qb2 }
9... Qxc3+ 10. Bd2 { The point. Black cannot play ...Qb2 now. } 10... Qa3 11.
h3 Nh6 12. g4
{ White has returned the pawn but Black's pieces are so badly placed. } *

