1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav defence is one of the oldest and the most solid systems around. In my database, it dates back to 1837. However, Wikipedia claims that the opening was analyzed as far back as 1590!     The popularity of the opening exploded in the 1920s, as many masters of the Slav descent helped develop the theory of the opening, including Alapin, Alekhine, Bogoljubov and Vidmar.   The Slav defence was also extensively played during the Alekhine - Euwe match and several other World Championship matches since. }
3. Nf3
{ White intends to keep the option where to development the b1-Knight open. It can go to either d2 or c3 in the future.  It is also possible to start with  3.Nc3  with its own pros and cons. The move-order starting with  3.Nf3  conforms better to our setup in question. }
3... Nf6
{ Black usually replies with  3...Nf6  or  3...e6  here.  3...Bf5  is a common mistake and  3...Bg4  is simply, but strongly replied with  4.Ne5  . }
4. g3
{ A very interesting and solid system which is quite underestimated in my opinion, like many good things. This option isn't even mentioned in the Wikipedia article about the Slav defence!  From the perspective of this repertoire, it makes the most sense to choose something that involves g3. GM Boris Avrukh has a pretty good course on  4.Qb3  , which is also a solid option involving setups with g3. So it made not much sense for me to go down that road. }
4... g6
{ The most solid response against the 4. g3 system and the one likely to be preferred at higher levels.   In general, the Slav setup in the centre complements the Kingside fianchetto well. For example, we have the Schlechter setup, which has a very solid reputation. This is no exception.   One of the problems Black faces with the Slav pawn-structure/setup is the placement of his light-squared Bishop. Not having to move the e-pawn helps with this. }
5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O dxc4
{ 6...dxc4  is a natural move. It is important to understand what happens if Black takes the pawn. This position can arise from many different setups. }
7. a4 { The natural response, preventing Black from playing ...b5 } 7... Ne4
{ Black essentially tries to make White's task of capturing the pawn on c4 harder by forcing White to play Na3 and Qc2. If White has to play Qc2, it exposes the White Queen to potential attacks from the Black Knight from b4. It is also useful for Black to get the Knight from f6 to d6.   Just like how the White Knight on d3 works well in tandem with the fianchettoed Bishop in many Catalan positions, likewise, the Black Knight is well-placed on d6, rather than f6. ...Ne4 helps Black to transfer the Knight to d6, from where it improves it's position and also helps defend the c4-pawn. }
8. Qc2
{ Again, the most natural move, attacking both the e4-Knight, the c4-pawn and making an advance towards the control of the centre. }
8... Nd6
{ Black has defended the c4-pawn and also threatens to develop ...Bf5 with tempo. }
9. e4
{ In a way White is forced to start with  9.e4  over  9.Na3  , as Black was threatening to play  9...Bf5  .    One of the threats is already to play e5. Here, White makes good use of the Black Knight's relocation from f6 to d6. If the Knight was on f6, the operation with e4/e5 would weaken the d5-square.   However, with the Black Knight on d6, the weakening of the d5-square isn't as serious. Nevertheless, e5 also weakens the d4-square, and as such White needs to be careful on the timing of the move. }
9... Na6
{ The natural developing place for the Knight. The move is all the more logical considering that White has just weakened the squares b4 and d3 in the last few moves. }
10. Na3
{ White places his Knight on a standard square. The White Queen can generally go to e2 which is a safe square and the typical place where the Queen is placed. }
10... O-O 11. Rd1
{ White is of course not in a hurry to capture Nxc4 and prefers to preserve the option of taking it with e5, Nxc4 as well. }
11... Nb4 12. Qe2
{ The standard square for the Queen in situations where White has moved the e-pawn forward. }
12... Nd3 13. e5
{ The standard approach. White prefers to capture on c4 with the Knight whenever possible, which is also a theme commonly shared with the Caro-Kann. }
13... Nxc1
{ It seems a bit odd for the Knight to have spent so many tempos to get to d3 and finally exchange itself away for a Bishop that hasn't moved the entire game. }
14. Raxc1 Ne8 15. Nxc4 Nc7 16. Nfd2
{ White has a slight, but decent edge.   The control over the squares c5 and d5 will be useful and Nb3, Ne3 is a possible example for the placement of the Knights. The Knight can also control the c5-square from e4.   In general if White manages to achieve d5, White will have an excellent position, which was how the game Kryvoruchko - Aditya, 2019 went. }
